45451.base_text:
And you become a forest in a furtive lake;
The dark pines of your mind reach downward,
You dream in the green of your time,
Your memory is a row of sinking pines.

45451.base_text: When I was little, my dad used to come tuck me in at night, and sometimes I’d blink and he’d disappear.

variants.text: He’d be sitting on my bed, singing or smoothing my sheets or telling a story, warm and alive, and between one blink and the next he’d be gone.

45451.base_text: My heart would thump and I’d clutch the blanket, terrified, eyes thrashing back and forth across the dark spaces of my room like a trapped bird looking for a way out, looking for him, but he’d be gone, and I’d be alone.

Our story.

45462.base_text: In sixth grade I had a brief friendship with a weird, indrawn kid with the same unhealthy imagination as me.

variants.text: In sixth grade I had a brief friendship with a weird, indrawn kid with the same unhealthy imagination as me.

45462.base_text: He liked to possible.

When you catch something from the corner of your eye, he’d explained, and it looks for an instant like something fantastic—a witch’s face in a hedge, a huge monstrous far-off thing instead of a tiny nearby insect—instead of correcting your perceptions, you let yourself keep believing in that first impression for as long as you can.

45462.base_text: You possible it.
Hold it in your head, your mental model of what’s real.

variants.text: Hold it in your head, your mental model of what’s real.

45462.base_text: Keep your mind from asserting the boring truth it thinks it knows and trust the one your senses first perceived.

45462.base_text: And I’d tried this, with him and on my own, off and on for a few weeks until I scared myself because I was getting too good at it.
